URL reference: https://vegastack.com/community/guides/kubernetes-secrets-enterprise-security-implementation
DateReviewed: 2025-11-07
Description: The article on tap today looks at secret management in the enterprise context. They explain tha by using K8s in a large enterprise, it can quickly turn into a nightmare, having to manage the secrets for all apps in a secure way. Add in things like rotation and having to abide by proper govenance policies, it can be prohibitive. After a bit more background, we get to the actual proposals - things like an external secrets operator, automatic rotation, and fine grained access control policies, among many others. They recommend using an integrated platform, for ease of use and consistency. They claim this can cut security incidents and save time and money. Interesting piece.
BottomLine: Article on issues surrounding Enterprise secrets in Kubernetes and how to approach them
==
URL reference: https://community.hpe.com/t5/the-cloud-experience-everywhere/companies-are-moving-to-kubernetes-but-secrets-security-can-be/ba-p/7254840
DateReviewed: 2025-11-08
Description: Our article postulates about secret security with the adoption of Kubernetes to deploy to. After a bit of background, we're down to brass tacks - why does secret mgmt need attention? They point out older practices like hardcoded creds or hand-rotated ones aren't keeping up with today's envs. They point out how things can be risky, and explain it's our job to manage such risk. What they advance to help with this is the Secrets store CSI Driver, which allows secrets to be stored in an extrenal store. It checks all the boxes - encryption, rotation, granualar access and audit logging. They give some real world example use cases, talk strategic benefits before finishing up with talking about security as scale.
BottomLine: Interesting approach to secret security on Kubernetes
