URL reference: https://docs.cosmonic.com/securely-deploy-mcp-on-kubernetes/
DateReviewed: 2025-11-09
Description: Today's article does a dive into deploying MCP securely on Kubernetes. They talk about the Model Context Protocol, how it began and point out the issues it can have as background. They talk about using WASM to mitigate risks, and show us a diagram of dataflows. This is a walkthrough, so they start with the bits we'll need to get this working, including NodeJS, NPM and wash. We need also to grab a plugin, the OpenAPI2MCP connector, to have things happen. They go through setting up our dev area we will connect MCP to, generate the configs, and finally dig into the MCP server. We spin up the MCP server, and then we connect to a model so we can get work done. They use Goose as the client, which can conect to a lot of models, and explain how ngrok is set up to forward locally. You have to configure Goose, which they talk about, and when that is done, we are ready to go. We can then ask a question and the model will return an answer. Now that this is done, we can publish and make available our model as an OCI image. They then show how to do this, so anyone can ask your model questions.
BottomLine: Great walkthrough of setting up AI to MCP securely on Kubernetes
